Introduction¶

Google Trends gives us an estimate of search volume. Let's explore if search popularity relates to other kinds of data. Perhaps there are patterns in Google's search volume and the price of Bitcoin or a hot stock like Tesla. Perhaps search volume for the term "Unemployment Benefits" can tell us something about the actual unemployment rate?

Data Sources:

  • Unemployment Rate from FRED
  • Google Trends
  • Yahoo Finance for Tesla Stock Price
  • Yahoo Finance for Bitcoin Stock Price

What do the Search Numbers mean?¶

We can see from our DataFrames that Google's search interest ranges between 0 and 100. But what does that mean? Google defines the values of search interest as:

Numbers represent search interest relative to the highest point on the chart for the given region and time. A value of 100 is the peak popularity for the term. A value of 50 means that the term is half as popular. A score of 0 means there was not enough data for this term.

Basically, the actual search volume of a term is not publicly available. Google only offers a scaled number. Each data point is divided by the total searches of the geography and time range it represents to compare relative popularity.

For each word in your search, Google finds how much search volume in each region and time period your term had relative to all the searches in that region and time period. It then combines all of these measures into a single measure of popularity, and then it scales the values across your topics, so the largest measure is set to 100. In short: Google Trends doesn’t exactly tell you how many searches occurred for your topic, but it does give you a nice proxy.

Here are the Google Trends Search Parameters that I used to generate the .csv data:

  • "Tesla", Worldwide, Web Search
  • "Bitcoin", Worldwide, News Search
  • "Unemployment Benefits", United States, Web Search

Use Styling for display¶

Unfortunately, as datetime objects, the months are displayed as a full date. If we want to keep them as datetime, nothing we can do.

But if it's just for display purpose, I can always change them back to a string with the right format: df_btc_search.MONTH.dt.strftime("%Y-%m")

In [29]:
df_btc_search.MONTH.dt.strftime("%Y-%m")[:3]
Out[29]:
0    2014-09
1    2014-10
2    2014-11
Name: MONTH, dtype: object

Or I can use styling. Every dataframe has its Styler object accessible by its .style property, and we changed this df.style object, not the dataframe itself.

df_btc_search.style.format({'MONTH': lambda t: t.strftime("%Y-%m")})

Careful! The returning object is NOT a dataframe — it is an object of the class Styler.

Unfortunately, if displayed, it displays the WHOLE table, and we can't manipulate it with slicers or .head() like a real df.

So we have to use the .hide() function on the Styler:          (or .hide_index() if pandas version < 1.4.0)

In [30]:
df_btc_search_styler = df_btc_search.style.format({'MONTH': lambda t: t.strftime("%Y-%m")})  # we create a new Styler object
df_btc_search_styler.hide_index(pd.IndexSlice[4:])
Out[30]:
  MONTH BTC_NEWS_SEARCH
0 2014-09 5
1 2014-10 4
2 2014-11 4
3 2014-12 4

Converting from Daily to Monthly Data¶

Pandas .resample() documentation

We have quite a few options depending what data we want. First of all, even before resampling, the data about TESLA stock values looked like this:

In [32]:
df_tesla[:2]
Out[32]:
MONTH TSLA_WEB_SEARCH TSLA_USD_CLOSE
0 2010-06-01 3 4.766
1 2010-07-01 3 3.988

So we don't know if the TSLA_USD_CLOSE is the avg value of the whole month. Or if it's the closing date value of that particular day, and it's just sampled every month.

Based on that, the .resample() function could be chained to a .mean(), a .first() or a .last() function, depending if we want the average value or the first value of the month or the last value of the month.

Also, the "rule" parameter in the .resample() function can take the argument 'M' or 'MS' depending if we want the first or the last day of the month.

In [33]:
df_btc_price_monthly = df_btc_price.resample('M', on='DATE').last()
df_btc_price_monthly[:2]
Out[33]:
DATE CLOSE VOLUME
DATE
2014-09-30 2014-09-30 386.944000 34707300.0
2014-10-31 2014-10-31 338.321014 12545400.0

Notice that we have DATE as index and as a column now.

In [34]:
df_btc_price_monthly.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)  # to get back to default index and DATE as a normal column
df_btc_price_monthly[:2]
Out[34]:
DATE CLOSE VOLUME
0 2014-09-30 386.944000 34707300.0
1 2014-10-31 338.321014 12545400.0

Alternatively, we could use the group_keys=False parameter in pandas 1.5.0 to avoid this index issue.

In [35]:
print(df_btc_search.shape)
print(df_btc_price_monthly.shape)

(73, 2)
(73, 3)

Now we have 73 rows in our price data - the same as our search data.

Notebook Formatting & Style Helpers¶

At this point, you might have seen this warning below from Matplotlib:

This is not an error, but an FYI to be explicit about which datetime converter to use. We have a timeline on our x-axis after all. To address this simply follow the instructions in the warning message and add the following code:

In [38]:
# Register date converters to avoid warning messages
from pandas.plotting import register_matplotlib_converters
register_matplotlib_converters()

When working with time series, it's often quite difficult to get the tick marks on charts looking the way you want to. This is why we have Locator helpers.

Using Locators we can change our x-axis from looking like this:

to looking like this:

The first step is importing matplotlib.dates. This is where all the date plotting capabilities live.

Next, we need a YearLocator() and a MonthLocator() objects, which will help Matplotlib find the years and the months. Then we also need a DateFormatter(), which will help us specify how we want to display the dates.

In [39]:
import matplotlib.dates as mdates
# Create locators for ticks on the time axis
years = mdates.YearLocator()
months = mdates.MonthLocator()
years_formatter = mdates.DateFormatter('%Y')

How to add tick formatting for dates on the x-axis.

In [40]:
plt.figure(figsize=(14,8), dpi=120)
plt.xticks(fontsize=14, rotation=45)
plt.title("Tesla Web Search vs Price", fontsize=18)
plt.xlim([df_tesla.MONTH.min(), df_tesla.MONTH.max()])

ax1 = plt.gca()
ax2 = ax1.twinx()

ax1.plot(df_tesla.MONTH, df_tesla.TSLA_USD_CLOSE, 'r', linewidth=3)
ax2.plot(df_tesla.MONTH, df_tesla.TSLA_WEB_SEARCH, 'b', linewidth=3)

ax1.set_ylim(0, 600)
ax1.set_ylabel('TSLA Stock Price', color='r', fontsize=14)
ax2.set_ylabel('Search Trend', color='b', fontsize=14)
plt.setp(ax1.get_yticklabels(), fontsize=14)
plt.setp(ax2.get_yticklabels(), fontsize=14)

# Adding tick marks to the x-axis
ax1.xaxis.set_major_locator(years)
ax1.xaxis.set_major_formatter(years_formatter)
ax1.xaxis.set_minor_locator(months)

plt.show()

What is this telling us? We see that searches for "Unemployment Benefits" happen before the actual official unemployment rate goes up. Similarly, the search popularity for the term goes down before the unemployment rate decreases. In other words, these searches seem to act as a leading economic indicator for the unemployment rate (which is a lagging indicator).

ax1.plot(df_ue_2020.MONTH, df_ue_2020.UNRATE, 'rebeccapurple', linewidth=3) # Rolling mean 6 months for the Web Search y-data
ax2.plot(df_ue_2020.MONTH, df_ue_2020.UE_BENEFITS_WEB_SEARCH, 'dodgerblue', linewidth=3) # Rolling mean 6 months for the Web Search y-data

# ax1.set_ylim(3, 10.5)
ax1.set_ylabel('FRED Unemployment (U/E) Rate', color='rebeccapurple', fontsize=16)
ax2.set_ylabel('Search Trend', color='dodgerblue', fontsize=16)
plt.setp(ax1.get_yticklabels(), fontsize=14)
plt.setp(ax2.get_yticklabels(), fontsize=14)

plt.show()

What we see is not pretty. The US unemployment rate spiked to unprecedented levels during the COVID pandemic, dwarfing the levels seen during the financial crisis. Let's hope the recovery will be swifter this time.

Learning Points & Summary¶

In this lesson we looked at how to:

  • How to use .describe() to quickly see some descriptive statistics at a glance.

  • How to use .resample() to make a time-series data comparable to another by changing the periodicity, and chain it with .mean(), .first() or .last()

  • How to use "rule" parameter in .resample() (e.g. 'M' or 'MS'), and the group_keys=False to avoid duplicating the index. Or else, using reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True) to reset the index

  • How to work with matplotlib.dates Locators to better style a timeline (e.g., an axis on a chart).

  • How to use .isna().any().any() or .isna().values

  • The fact that True + True -> 2 so we can sum booleans to find the number of NaN values with .isna().values.sum()

  • How to change the resolution of a chart using the figure's dpi

  • How to create dashed '--' and dotted '-.' lines using linestyles

  • How to use different kinds of markers (e.g., 'o' or '^') on charts.

  • Fine-tuning the styling of Matplotlib charts by using limits, labels, linewidth and colours (both in the form of named colours and HEX codes).

  • Using .grid() to help visually identify seasonality in a time series.

  • Review of using Logical Operators (| & ~), .dropna(), converting to Datetime pd.to_datetime(), and DataFrame.rolling(window=6).mean()

  • Converting a Datetime Series into a formatted String Series: Series.dt.strftime("%Y-%m")

  • Each Dataframe has a Styler object attribute, from which we can derive to display the df the way we want. Examples:

    df_btc_search_styler = df_btc_search.style.format({'MONTH': lambda t: t.strftime("%Y-%m")})
df_btc_search_styler.hide_index(pd.IndexSlice[4:])

  • Finding the current Pandas version with pd.__version__
